        Capital Gains Tax When Selling Your Home in Queensland: the Main Residence Exemption
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        For most sellers, CGT is not an issue. But the rules have enough nuance that assuming you are fully exempt without checking can be a costly mistake.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Capital gains tax is not something most homeowners think about when they sell. For many, the main residence exemption removes any liability entirely, and the sale proceeds arrive without any tax consequence beyond what has already been paid as income. But the exemption is not unconditional, and there are common situations where sellers discover too late that their CGT position was not as straightforward as they assumed. Understanding the basics before you list is a basic act of financial self-protection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What capital gains tax is and when it applies to property</h2>
      <p>CGT is a tax on the profit you make when you sell a capital asset. It was introduced in Australia on 20 September 1985. Any property acquired on or after that date is potentially subject to CGT when sold. The taxable gain is the difference between the cost base (broadly, what you paid for the property plus certain capital costs) and the sale proceeds. That gain is added to your assessable income for the year and taxed at your marginal rate, after applying any applicable discount.</p>

      <p>For properties held for more than 12 months, individual taxpayers and trusts receive a 50% CGT discount. That means only half the capital gain is included in taxable income. For most Australian homeowners selling a property they have lived in, the main residence exemption applies before the discount even becomes relevant.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The main residence exemption: how it fully exempts your home</h2>
      <p>The main residence exemption is set out in Division 118 of the Income Tax Assessment Act 1997. It provides a full exemption from CGT on the disposal of a dwelling that has been your main residence for your entire ownership period. If you bought a home, lived in it as your principal place of residence for the whole time you owned it, and then sold it, you will generally owe no CGT on the gain, regardless of how much the property has increased in value.</p>

      <p>The exemption applies to the land on which the dwelling sits, up to a maximum of 2 hectares. Structures connected to and adjacent to the dwelling are also covered. A standard suburban house and garden in Brisbane comfortably falls within these parameters.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Partial exemption scenarios: when the exemption is not all-or-nothing</h2>
      <p>The exemption becomes partial rather than full in certain common situations. The most frequent ones are renting out part or all of the property during the ownership period, and using part of the home for income-producing purposes such as a home office where actual expenses have been claimed.</p>

      <p>If you rented out a room, converted a portion of the property to an Airbnb listing, or ran a business from a dedicated part of the home, the ATO will apportion the exemption. The proportion of the property used for income-producing purposes, and the period for which that use occurred, both factor into the calculation. The gain attributable to the income-producing portion is taxable; the rest remains exempt. Getting this calculation right requires a tax adviser who can look at the specifics of your situation, not a general estimate.</p>

      <p>Home office claims that are limited to running costs such as electricity and internet, calculated using the ATO's fixed rate method, do not affect the CGT exemption. It is only when you claim actual occupancy costs, such as a proportion of mortgage interest or rent, that the exemption is partially lost. This distinction trips up more sellers than it should.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 6-year rule: renting out your home without losing the exemption</h2>
      <p>One of the more useful provisions in the CGT rules is the 6-year absence rule. If you move out of your main residence and rent it out, you can continue to treat it as your main residence for CGT purposes for up to 6 years, provided you do not elect any other property as your main residence during that period.</p>

      <p>This matters for sellers who moved out of a property they once lived in, rented it for several years, and are now selling it. If the rental period was less than 6 years and no other property was nominated as a main residence during that time, the full exemption may still apply. The 6-year clock resets each time you move back in, meaning the rule can be applied across multiple periods of absence.</p>

      <p>If the rental period exceeded 6 years, a partial exemption applies. The gain is apportioned between the exempt period (the period of actual residence plus the allowed 6-year absence) and the taxable period (anything beyond that). Again, the precise calculation depends on your specific dates and circumstances.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Two properties: you can only nominate one main residence at a time</h2>
      <p>A common scenario arises when sellers purchase a new property before selling the old one, or when couples each own a property before moving in together. The rule is that each taxpayer can only have one main residence at a time for CGT purposes. When you own two properties simultaneously, you must decide which one is your main residence, and the other is treated as an investment property during the overlap period.</p>

      <p>There is a 6-month transitional period that provides some relief: when you are selling one property and have already acquired a new main residence, you can treat both as your main residence for up to 6 months, provided the property you are selling was your main residence for a continuous period of at least 3 months in the 12 months before the sale. This is useful but limited, and does not cover extended settlement periods or situations where the overlap exceeds 6 months.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The CGT event date: it is the contract date, not settlement</h2>
      <p>A practical point that surprises some sellers: the CGT event generally occurs on the date the contract of sale is signed, not the settlement date. This matters for annual tax calculations, especially for sales that contract in one financial year and settle in the next. If you sign a contract in late June 2027 and settle in August 2027, the CGT event falls in the 2026-27 tax year, even though you receive the proceeds in 2027-28.</p>

      <p>This also affects the 12-month discount. The relevant holding period is measured from acquisition to the contract date of sale. A property purchased in June 2026 and sold by contract in May 2027 would not attract the 50% discount, even if the settlement date falls after the 12-month mark. If you are close to the 12-month threshold, the contract date is the date to watch.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Inherited properties: different rules apply</h2>
      <p>Selling an inherited property introduces a different set of rules, and the outcome varies depending on when the deceased acquired the property and their tax status at the time of death.</p>

      <p>Pre-CGT properties (acquired before 20 September 1985) are generally fully exempt from CGT regardless of the inheritor's circumstances. For properties acquired after that date, the inherited property takes on a cost base that depends on whether it was the deceased's main residence and whether they were an Australian tax resident. In some cases the exemption passes to the beneficiary; in others it does not. Selling an inherited property without obtaining specific advice first is a situation where well-intentioned assumptions regularly produce unexpected tax bills.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Get specific tax advice before you list</h2>
      <p>The reason to go through all of this is not to make selling your home feel complicated. For most sellers in Brisbane's inner east who have lived in their property as their principal place of residence throughout their ownership, the exemption applies fully and there is nothing to worry about. The reason to understand the rules is to know whether you are one of the cases where the exemption is not straightforward.</p>

      <p>If you have rented the property at any point, used part of it for income-producing purposes, owned it for less than 12 months, or inherited it, a conversation with a qualified tax accountant before you list is a reasonable step. The cost of that advice is a fraction of the potential CGT liability if you discover the situation after the fact. Your agent can provide you with a recommended contact if you do not already have an accountant who handles property.</p>

